    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "49b33c0e_87b31c61",
        "filename": "skylark/skylarkproto/type.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 55,
      "author": {
        "id": 1002539
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-05-08T18:23:21Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e Is it actually not possible to implicitly default a oneof?\n\u003e \n\nI decided not to do it, because there\u0027ll be no way to check which oneof alternative is currently set. Note that Python API has no implicit defaults at all. Implicit defaults is our skylark thingy to simplify code that generates protos, since we\u0027ll be doing that a lot.\n\n\u003e I find it surprising that setting multiple members of a oneof is silently ignored rather than being a runtime error:\n\u003e https://developers.google.com/protocol-buffers/docs/reference/python-generated#oneof\n\u003e \n\nI believe Python API works same way as our skylark API does: setting one alternative resets the rest. E.g. see this example:\n\n  message \u003d Foo()\n  message.name \u003d \"Bender\"\n  assert message.HasField(\"name\")\n  message.serial_number \u003d 2716057\n  assert message.HasField(\"serial_number\")\n  assert not message.HasField(\"name\")\n\nNotice how setting \u0027serial_number\u0027 resets \u0027name\u0027.\n\n\u003e Given such behavior I would not be extra surprised if they also had something strange like \"whichever oneof you look at first is auto-initialized\".\n\nNope, they don\u0027t mutate anything on reads.",
      "parentUuid": "241db19b_9afb8179",
      "revId": "481e78f2cded17ebc9e17a1a2220a061d94cd469",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
